text: Here's an equation for you:  Gladiator + Titanic + Dante's Peak = Pompeii  I think I pretty much nailed it. Kudos to me!  Okay, now on a more serious note. There is a reason why someone would want to make a big budget movie about this theme. If you search the net, and even here on youtube, you will find documentaries about this tragedy.  So first, a bit of history. Vesuvius was a tragedy because it was unprecedented in the Roman Empire. The word 'volcano' comes directly from the god of fire, Vulcan (in Latin, Vulcanus); there was no word for it back then. When the mountain first started to erupt, the fact that people chose to stay in the city is what doomed them. It was through Pliny the Younger, who witnessed the event, that a first, extensively documented account of an active volcano's behavior was registered - and from this, the reason why nowadays volcanologists have a category for volcanoes the likes of Mount Vesuvius named 'Plinian'.  But, returning to magnitude of events, the neighboring cities of Mount Vesuvius were wiped out, no survivors whatsoever. And until then, the Romans hadn't experienced so many losses of civilian life in the very heart of their empire - numbers say 16 thousand -, to forces of nature, no less.  So yes, I can see there's an appeal to making a movie about the theme. Now, is the movie going to be accurate in the events? Well, there's always the dramatization, which is really up to the viewer. On another note, specifically the story, it doesn't mean the protagonists perish, likely as it may sound. One'll have to see it to learn it, after all.  But what I think a movie like this may bring, is a verdict to whether or not Paul W. S. Anderson is able to bring about a decent movie to the table instead of some anachronistic flick - the fact that 'The Three Musketeers' has ships flying through the air with a sort of blimp-like sails in their cover is one of the reasons why I stayed away from that movie -, or he should keep to poorly fleshed-out zombie flicks that have lost any resemblance to the franchise they're supposed to be based on. Some of his movies can surprise you in a good way. Maybe this will be one.

text: Every Hollywood movie is the same now. Completely ridiculous, totally improbable crap with tons of visual effects that looks like a video game. If I wanted to play video games I'd play video games. At least I can participate.  You can pretty much substitute the main characters, change the location, and the name of the movie and you don't need to see any other blockbusters. Same shit every time.  I guess that's what sells to the shallow, immature audience these days. Any movie where something doesn't explode for 5 sec and Americans fall asleep causing them to choke on their popcorn. And we wouldn't want that, would we?  I'm the opposite. Give me a good story and I'll be glued to the screen. Give me this blockbuster crap and I fall asleep. text: This is so wrong. Way to ruin a story. Pompeii wasn't "Rome-ish" like they portreited it. Pompeii was a place where the rich would go on vacation.¬† Also, Vesuvius' eruption wasn't explosive like in the movie. Precisely what made people underreact and stay in their homes until it was too late. Some fled to the beach when the air became too thick with ash and the streets filled with pumice. Fire and lava didn't kill them - the ones that weren't mortally hit by big pieces of pumice died by¬†asphyxiation. I have always been drawn by Pompeii and Vesuvius. I wish they would have done a good job but I guess I can't ask too much of a movie made for the masses. "Entertainment".

text: Why can't Hollywood produce a serious movie anymore?  It's one overplayed, CGI piece of trash after another.  I guess it LOOKS cool and all, but there is absolutely no substance in these movies.  NONE.  Modern cinematography has the potential to produce legendary, original material, but that's just not what we get.  The story of Pompeii is legendary.  It could be the next Lawrence of Arabia.  But all people want is shallow, schizophrenic nonsense.  No doubt with this movie absolutely zero historical literacy as well.

text: I studied the disaster of Vesuvius for 10years for the novel Havens of Pompeii - there was no lava in the eruption, the magma was too explosive. Most people hid in their homes to wait out the disaster - as the bodies were all found in buildings. Death came when all that explosive magma, froth, ash and debris - which shot 30km into the air, fell back on itself and formed the avalanches which wiped out Herculaneum and Pompeii. From eye-witness accounts and records of Pliny and others, falling debris was never larger than a cannon ball. Boats had to steer south due to the heavy ash fall. AND only pompeii holds the cast mummies due to the ash fall. Herculaneum holds skeletons. Sorry, but this was really OVER-exaggerated. ...¬†

text: Alright I just came back from watching the movie, and I was surprised. I have never been much of a Paul W.S Anderson fan so my expectations were quite low, but he really stepped up his game. The drama elements and character building are a bit shallow and the overall story is too generic, but if you can look past that and just focus on the entertainment, this movie is really enjoyable. Being able to relive a fraction of what occurred at Pompeii and seeing Mt Vesuvius explode on the big screen is exceptional. Kit Harrington and Emily Brown also do a good job carrying the movie, even with cheesy dialogue. I also liked the casting for the supporting actors,¬†¬†Kiefer Sutherland, Jared Harris and Carrie Ann-Moss are all actors whom I admire and although they only play minor characters and don't get enough chances to shine, their presence really levitates the movie... Overall I'd recommend this movie to anyone who is interested in the subject and isn't too concerned with substance.¬†

text: Stop comparing it to Titanic. Do your research. 79AD - eruption of Vesuvius. Its real. The gladiator battles did happen. Pompeii had its own amphitheatre (two in fact, a large one and a small one). It was a holiday city for the Romans. People lived there all year around, but they also had Roman families travel there for the summer, which in 79AD is when the eruption occurred.¬†  Its not a "Gladiator 2" movie or anything based on Titanic. Its just Hollywood's spin on a famous historical event.

text: Great visual effects. Though from what I read, showing a thumb up during a gladiator fight is a historical fallacy picked up wrongly by many others. When the thumb was up, it meant thing - death, for it resembled the sword being taken out of the sheath. When a fist was shown, symbolizing the sword staying within the sheath, it meant mercy. ¬†  I have read various interpretations, sometimes quite contrary, but obviously the "Like" thumb that many deem as a good, positive sign, as "spare one's life" meant quite the opposite. ¬† ¬† ¬†

text: The movie was amazing. Idk why some people are hating on it. It doesn't matter if it isn't 100 % accurate. It's based on a real tragedy that took many lives and at the same time it's combined with a love story. And honestly movies like this are meant to be dramatized because they show what people affected by these disasters felt they were seeing. I mean to us it's a natural disaster but to them it was the end of there world. They never witnessed anything like it before. So the reason this movie is dramatized and over exaggerated a little is because the movie director does not want to show what people think is true but to show what people in pompeii felt they were seeing through there own eyes.

The biggest flaw in this movie is the emphasis they put on the super-heated falling rocks that probably killed everyone before the ash cloud came. In reality the people of Pompeii died from the super-heated ash. That really helped preserve the whole city; if it was the other way around there wouldn't be a town to preserve. They kinda mixed it up for theatrical effect, but anyway, it was enjoyable otherwise.

text: I've seen this movie and even heard the filmmakers' commentary, wherein it's claimed that the effects of the 79 AD eruption of Mt. Vesuvius did include a tsunami. Now, POMPEII is a 2014 film, pretty recent, but it's first and foremost a good old-fashioned disaster film with a love story worthy of TITANIC. But I'd like to find a documentary or book with the LATEST research on the eruption that buried Pompeii. For many years it was believed that Pliny the Younger exaggerated in his account of the disaster, and now researchers are saying, "Oh, wait--he didn't exaggerate."

text: It was a stupid movie that merely recycled plot elements and action sequences from better films. It didn't even know what it wanted to be---a disaster flick, a gladiator film, Romeo & Juliet--? The writing and direction were so lazy and repetitive, the characters so cliched,  that a huge, cataclysmic volcano actually managed to be boring. It was pulled from my local theater after only a week---that's how bad it was.
